(2651, 306, 'show_information', '<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Written by Shirley Lauro, a powerful, true drama of six women who went to Vietnam: </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">nurses, a Red Cross volunteer and a USO country-western singer</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. The latter is booked to entertain the troops by an unscrupulous agent. Follow each young woman’s story before, during, and after her tour in the war-torn nation. It was named “The most enduring play on Vietnam in the nation,” by The Vietnam Vets Association.</span>'),
(2652, 306, '_show_information', 'field_58a2597a1e75b'),
(2653, 306, 'additional_information', 'Director: Mia Self\r\n<h4>Support and Sponsors</h4>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This project is supported by the</span><a href=\"http://www.ncarts.org/\"> <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">N.C. Arts Council</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, a division of the Department of Natural &amp; Cultural Resources. </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Supported by a grant from the Paul Green Foundation, Inc. Serving the Arts and Human Rights since 1982 Chapel Hill, North Carolina.</span>\r\n\r\n<i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">A Piece of My Heart</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> is part of the</span><a href=\"http://www.redcross.org/enc\"> <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">American Red Cross Eastern North Carolina Region\'s</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> 100th anniversary celebration.</span>\r\n<h4>To Any Soldier</h4>\r\nThursday, May 11 at 7:00pm\r\nLobby of the Cantey V. Sutton Theatre\r\n\r\nMeet Kathryn Watson Quigg, the author of <em>To Any Soldier, a Novel of Vietnam Letters</em>. Kathryn will talk about the novel and several of the letters from the book will be performed by local actors!\r\n<h4>A Panel Discussion with Larry Hines and James R. Wilson</h4>\r\nThursday, May 18 at 7:00pm\r\nLobby of the Cantey V. Sutton Theatre\r\n\r\nPatrick Torres (RLT Artistic Director) will interview Larry Hines, a Red Cross Volunteer or \"Donut Dolly\" in Vietnam from 1968-69, and James R. Wilson a journalist and Army press officer in Vietnam and author of <em>Landing Zones: Southern Veterans Remember Vietnam</em>, to breathe real life experiences into the characters of <em>A Piece of My Heart</em>. No ticket or reservation required.'),
