(968, 4, '2017-04-05 12:00:53', '2017-04-05 16:00:53', 'Thank you to everyone who auditioned -- we cannot thank you enough for sharing your talents with us!\r\n\r\nThe following people have been called back for roles in RLT\'s production of <em>Avenue Q</em>.<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<strong>Men</strong>:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Michael Bacigalupo</li>\r\n 	<li>Aaron Boles</li>\r\n 	<li>Jon Parker Douglas</li>\r\n 	<li>Del Flack</li>\r\n 	<li>Isaiah Lewis</li>\r\n 	<li>Christopher J. Maxwell</li>\r\n 	<li>Freddy Perkins</li>\r\n 	<li>Matthew Sheaffer</li>\r\n 	<li>Bradley Waelbroeck</li>\r\n 	<li>Brett Yates</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Women</strong>:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Mary Bain</li>\r\n 	<li>Erin Brown</li>\r\n 	<li>Aubrey Comperatore</li>\r\n 	<li>Samantha Corey</li>\r\n 	<li>Sara Croninger</li>\r\n 	<li>Lydia D. Kinton</li>\r\n 	<li>Brandi Parker</li>\r\n 	<li>Molly Riddick</li>\r\n 	<li>Brett Williams</li>\r\n 	<li>Karen Williams</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nCallbacks are tonight, Wednesday 4/5 at 7:00PM in the Gaddy-Goodwin Teaching Theatre. More specific information regarding roles will be given at callbacks. Please dress comfortably and wear closed-toed shoes. We look forward to seeing you!', 'Callbacks for Avenue Q', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'callbacks-for-avenue-q', '', '', '2017-04-06 21:31:31', '2017-04-07 01:31:31', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8000/?p=968', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(969, 4, '2017-04-05 20:23:22', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'In 1936, a group of passionate local performers joined forces with technical workers from the Federal Theatre Project to begin a community theatre in Raleigh, joining a nation-wide movement of little theatres focused on intimate, non-commercial theater.\r\n\r\nCivic leader Cantey Venable Sutton pushed through bureaucratic red tape and galvanized the federal Works Progress Administration construction of the initial campus, which included a 300-seat proscenium theater, 2,000-seat outdoor amphitheater, and a Rose Garden.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_971\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"586\"]<img class=\" wp-image-971\" src=\"http://localhost:8000/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/The-Drunkard-1936.gif\" alt=\"A scene from The Drunkard, 1936\" width=\"586\" height=\"369\" /> The Drunkard, RLT\'s first production, 1936[/caption]\r\n\r\nIn 2000, the original theater was renamed in honor of Mrs. Sutton. RLT\'s annual performance awards, given each June, have been called \"Canteys\" in her honor for decades.\r\n\r\nRLT\'s founding united the spirit of the Little Theatre Movement with the mission of the Federal Theatre Project, which aimed to employ artists, create relevant art, and provide entertainment for low-income families. This commitment to accessibility defined the organization early on and continues today, with a focus on keeping ticket prices affordable, choosing accessible while challenging theatrical works, and opportunities for anyone in the community to be involved by getting on stage or working behind the scenes.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_972\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"567\"]<img class=\" wp-image-972\" src=\"http://localhost:8000/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Cinderella-1986.jpg\" alt=\"Cinderella, 1986\" width=\"567\" height=\"378\" /> Cinderella, 1986[/caption]\r\n\r\nWhile Raleigh has grown by leaps and bounds over the last 77 years, RLT has grown as well. In the 1960s a scene shop and dressing rooms were added on to the initial theater footprint to enable staff and volunteers to increase production capacity.\r\n\r\nIn the 1980s, a 150-seat black box, the Gaddy-Goodwin Teaching Theatre, was built to provide additional training opportunities for emerging artists. Around this time, the theater began an education program.\r\n\r\nIn the late 1990s, a lobby was added to the Cantey V. Sutton Theatre to enhance the patron experience, and a number of renovations upgraded the outdoor amphitheater.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_973\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"582\"]<img class=\"wp-image-973\" src=\"http://localhost:8000/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Joseph-And-The-Amazing-Technicolor-Dreamcoat-2002.jpg\" alt=\"Joseph And The Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat, 2002\" width=\"582\" height=\"437\" /> Joseph And The Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat, RLT Amphitheatre, 2002[/caption]\r\n\r\nThough a student or actor going on to become a professional in the performing arts is not the primary mission of RLT, a number of performers have gone on to acclaimed careers. Andy Griffith performed at RLT multiple times, including in a revival of \"The Drunkard\" in the 1951-52 season.\r\n\r\nOther notable performers and alumni include Randy Jones (later the cowboy in The Village People), Clay Aiken (platinum-selling recording artist), Anthony Roth Costanzo (made his debut as Prospero in \"The Enchanted Island\" at the Metropolitan Opera in 2012), and Laurel Harris (Elphaba in the national tour of “Wicked”).\r\n\r\nMany other performers have found rewarding experiences in the theater, made lifelong friends, and been challenged to grow creatively and technically in their time at RLT.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_974\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"570\"]<img class=\" wp-image-974\" src=\"http://localhost:8000/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Runaways-2015.jpg\" alt=\"Runaways, 2015\" width=\"570\" height=\"378\" /> Runaways, RLT Teens on Stage Production, 2015[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe education program was recognized with the 2002 Constance Welsh Theatre for Youth Award by the North Carolina Theatre Conference (NCTC). RLT was inducted in to the Raleigh Hall of Fame in 2007. In 2012, RLT received the Community Theatre Award from NCTC for the second time.\r\n\r\nWriting for the News and Observer in 2014, Roy Dicks said “RLT is redefining what you can expect from a community theatre.” RLT has won a number of the Independent Weekly\'s awards for Best Live Theatre, most recently in 2016.', 'Our History at a Glance', '', 'draft', 'closed', 'closed', '', '', '', '', '2017-04-05 20:23:22', '2017-04-06 00:23:22', '', 17, 'http://localhost:8000/?page_id=969', 0, 'page', '', 0),
